04044nam a22005895i 9780520944770DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20092009cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209447707 a10.1525/97805209447702doi  a(DE-B1597)647813  a(OCoLC)566119105  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aF203.5.M2bS38 2009eb 7aART0000002bisacsh04a725/.94097532221 aSavage, Kirk, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMonument Wars :bWashington, D.C., the National Mall, and the Transformation of the Memorial Landscape /cKirk Savage; ed. by Kirk Savage. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (408 p.) :b126 black-and-white photographs, 1 line drawing  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 A Monument to a Deceased Project -- t2 Covering Ground -- t3 The Mechanic Monster -- t4 Inventing Public Space -- t5 The Monument Transformed -- t6 The Conscience of the Nation -- t7 An End to War, an End to Monuments? -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tList of Illustrations -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe National Mall in Washington, D.C., is “a great public space, as essential a part of the American landscape as the Grand Canyon,” according to architecture critic Paul Goldberger, but few realize how recent, fragile, and contested this achievement is. In Monument Wars, Kirk Savage tells the Mall's engrossing story—its historic plan, the structures that populate its corridors, and the sea change it reveals regarding national representation. Central to this narrative is a dramatic shift from the nineteenth-century concept of a decentralized landscape, or “ground”-heroic statues spread out in traffic circles and picturesque parks-to the twentieth-century ideal of “space,” in which authority is concentrated in an intensified center, and the monument is transformed from an object of reverence to a space of experience. Savage's lively and intelligent analysis traces the refocusing of the monuments themselves, from that of a single man, often on horseback, to commemorations of common soldiers or citizens; and from monuments that celebrate victory and heroism to memorials honoring victims. An indispensable guide to the National Mall, Monument Wars provides a fresh and fascinating perspective on over two hundred years of American history.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMemorializationzUnited States. 0aMemorialszWashington (D.C.). 0aMonumentszWashington (D.C.). 4aArt. 4aGeneral. 7aART / General.2bisacsh1 aSavage, Kirk, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027133340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094477040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520944770423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520944770/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles